===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm}} {{term|Breteyne|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|Bretaigne|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|Britannia|lang=la}}, earlier ''Brittania'', from ''Brittani'' 'Britons', from British Celtic *''Pritani'' (cf. {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|Prydain}} 'Britain'), from {{proto|Celtic}} *''kʷritanī'' 'Picts', archaic form of *''kʷritenī'' (compare {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|Prydyn}} 'Picts', {{etyl|sga|-}} ''Cruthne, Cru(i)then-túath'' 'Pict-folk'), plural of *''kʷritus'' 'form' (compare {{etyl|cy}} {{term|pryd}} 'form, appearance', {{etyl|sga}} {{term|cruth}} 'id.'). A loan translation gave {{etyl|la}} {{term|Picti}}, 'Picts', literally 'the painted'.

